Dimensionality Reduction¶

MNIST dataset which is a set of images of handwritten digits https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/MNIST_database.

  • Apply a Random Forest classification algorithm to MNIST dataset
  • Perform dimensionality reduction of features using PCA and compare classification on the reduced dataset to that of original one
  • Apply dimensionality reduction techniques: t-SNE and LLE

Training a Random Forest Classifier, and evaluating its performance.

In [20]:
X_test, y_test =  test.iloc[:,1:].values, test.iloc[:,0].values
X_train, y_train = train.iloc[:,1:].values, train.iloc[:,0].values
In [21]:
import time
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
In [22]:
time_start=time.time()
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 100)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print('Model complete! Time elapsed: {} seconds'.format(time.time()-time_start))

Model complete! Time elapsed: 39.46743869781494 seconds
In [23]:
y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)
In [24]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report
In [25]:
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred_test)
print(f'Accuracy of our Random Forest Classifier model is {(accuracy*100)}%')

Accuracy of our Random Forest Classifier model is 96.86%

Using PCA to reduce the datasets dimensionality, with an explained variance ratio of 95%. Training a new Random Forest classifier on the reduced dataset and see how long it takes.

In [26]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

pca = PCA(0.95).fit(X_train)
In [27]:
pca_cum_var=np.cumsum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
dimension = np.argmax(pca_cum_var >=0.95) + 1
print(f'Number of dimensions needed to explain 95% variance ratio is {dimension}.')

Number of dimensions needed to explain 95% variance ratio is 154.
In [28]:
pca = PCA(n_components=154, random_state = 123)
pca_t = pca.fit_transform(df)
pca_df=pd.DataFrame(pca_t)
In [29]:
pca_t.shape
Out[29]:
(70000, 154)
In [30]:
train_pca=pca_df.iloc[:60000]
test_pca=pca_df.iloc[60000:]
In [31]:
print(train_pca.shape)
print(test_pca.shape)

(60000, 154)
(10000, 154)
In [32]:
X_train, y_train = train_pca.values, y_train
X_test, y_test = test_pca.values, y_test
In [33]:
time_start=time.time()
clf = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators = 100)
clf.fit(X_train, y_train)
print('Model complete! Time elapsed: {} seconds'.format(time.time()-time_start))

Model complete! Time elapsed: 81.33959436416626 seconds

The original model took 39 seconds to process, while the new model took 81 seconds. Second model took a lot longer to train.

In [34]:
y_pred_test = clf.predict(X_test)
accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test,y_pred_test)
print(f'Accuracy of our Random Forest Classifier model is {(accuracy*100)}%')

Accuracy of our Random Forest Classifier model is 95.06%

The original model had accuracy of 96.86% while the transformed data set has a slightly lower accuracy of 95.06%.

Comparing with other dimensionality methods: Locally Linear Embedding (LLE) or Multidimensional scaling (MDS).

In [38]:
from sklearn.manifold import LocallyLinearEmbedding
lle = LocallyLinearEmbedding(n_components=2, n_neighbors=10, random_state=41, n_jobs=1)
X_reduced_cr=lle.fit_transform(X_train)
In [42]:
plt.title("Dimensionality LLE", fontsize=14)
plt.scatter(X_reduced_cr[:, 0], X_reduced_cr[:, 1], c=y_train, cmap=plt.cm.hot)
plt.xlabel("$z_1$", fontsize=18)
plt.ylabel("$z_2$", fontsize=18)
plt.grid(True)
plt.show()

Compared to other models we can clearly see that Locally Linear Embedding model is not as efficient as other models due to long processing times. Current transformation and fitting took over half an hour of processing to complete and will difficult to work with.
